<br>
I started a character here some time ago, one that I really liked the idea behind. It was a human warrior, a worshiper of Karana. He was a sailor who came ashore at Qeynos and was setting about on a new career as an adventurer.<br>
<br>
Then I discovered a friend of mine  had created a gnome, and, since I wanted to hang out with him, and since getting from Qeynos to Ak'Anon is no small feat with a young'un when Highpass is not hunted day and night, and since we would have great trouble communicating for some time, I gave away all of my warriors goods and reincarnated as a gnomish cleric.<br>
<br>
I put some time into that cleric, completed several low level quests (got my framed backpack, for example), but I just don't like the character as much as I did my warrior. My friend is not playing much at all, so my reason for creating my cleric are faded.<br>
<br>
What I am looking for from you are suggestions and support. Tell me why I should actually love an impulsive gnomish cleric of Fizzlethorpe, who has heard there is actually a whole city of  his followers. Or tell me how it doesn't matter how much time you have put into a character; if it doesn't suit you start over. Or anything else that would help me push myself in one direction or another.<br>
<br>
Thank you for your comments. <p>_______________________________<BR>
Zambus Starcrafter<BR>
<BR></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/umaladominus.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Maladominus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 92<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/30/02 8:36:15 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1237.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Getting one's heart behind a character</span><hr size=1> Play what makes you happy.... play something that you know will suit you. Use your instincts. <br>
<br>
Play a main character that every time you come on the LogOn screen and you see him you say to yourself <br>
<br>
&quot;Oh yeah, that's me! That character is me. I am proud of this character, and every time I play him.... my heart is behind him 100 percent.&quot;  <br>
<br>
Don't play something solely because:  <br>
<br>
1) your friends expected you to do it <br>
<br>
2) your guild expected you to do it <br>
<br>
3) your guilty conscience is preventing you from changing (due to time and investment on an existing character) <br>
<br>
4) some geek in these forums told you that Gnomes are statistically sexier and more enjoyable characters to play than the rest <br>
<br>
Play what makes you happy!!  That's all that matters. <br>
<br>
A lot of people have an identity crisis when it comes to choosing the right character.  There is nothing wrong with that!  This is simply the process of trial and error and finding who you really are, and who you want to be in this game. Some players find the &quot;right type&quot; almost instantly when they start playing. Other players will have to fumble around with several characters until they can really find out whats best for them. <br>
<br>
Sometimes this identity crisis happens in real life too. A lot of people who are adults still have no clue what profession or career they really want. Sometimes they are still trying to figure out how they fit in with the rest of society. They keep looking and searching.  There is nothing wrong with this. It's human nature. <br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uvallshadowstrife.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Vall Shadowstrife</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Crime Lord</span><br>  Posts: 115<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/30/02 8:49:36 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1237.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Getting one's heart behind a character</span><hr size=1> Never get too attached to a character. Trust me on this one, nothing good comes from it. AtG, MUD I admin on, has one of those, &quot;You die once, you stay dead.&quot; rules. I've seen people freak out because they got too attached to a character and it got killed. <br>
